text: Lincolnenins A−D: Isomeric Bactericidal Bianthracenes from Streptomyces lincolnensis ⊥ Osama G. Mohamed, and Robert J. Capon* ABSTRACT: Cultivation proﬁling followed by chemical analysis of Streptomyces lincolnensis yielded four new isomeric bianthracenes, lincolnenins A−D (1−4), with relative stereostructures assigned on the basis of detailed spectroscopic analysis. Lincolnenins A (1) and B (2) exhibit restricted rotation about alternate bianthracene 9−9′ and 9−8′ bridges, respectively, and exist as single atropisomers, whereas C (3) and D (4) are thermally interconvertible atropisomers sharing a common 8−8′ bianthracene bridge. Absolute conﬁgurations were assigned to 1−4 on the basis of diagnostic ROESY correlations and ECD calculations, whereas acid-mediated dehydration of 1 led to formation and revision of the absolute conﬁguration of the biosynthetically related known Streptomyces antibiotic, setomimycin (5). Lincolnenin A (1) exhibited signiﬁcant bactericidal activity against multiple susceptible and drug-resistant Gram-positive pathogens (MIC99 < 2.0 μM), Mycobacterium tuberculosis H37Ra (MIC99 = 0.9 μM).

Antibiotic resistance is currently one the most serious threats to global healthcare, with the majority of frontline antibiotic classes being increasingly less eﬀective at controlling infectious disease. As a result, there is an urgent and compelling case for the discovery and development of new and improved antibiotics. During our ongoing investigations into natural products from Australian terrestrial and marine-derived bacteria, we discovered and reported many new antibiotic scaﬀolds, including the antimycobacterial wollamides,1 arancia- mycins2 and mollemycin A,3 and antibacterial heronapyr- roles,4,5 divirensols6 and trivirensols,7 and talaropeptides.8 In recent years, these eﬀorts have been enabled by the use of a fermentation system miniaturized 24-well microbioreactor (known in-lab as the MATRIX), which provides rapid, cost- eﬀective, and high-throughput cultivation proﬁling under multiple media conditions, including solid as well as shaken and static broth. In situ solvent extraction of MATRIX plates, integrated with HPLC-DAD-ESIMS chemical proﬁling, provides an eﬀective means to detect rare from common, and new from known natural products.8 While eﬀective at detecting new natural products in new bacterial isolates, we in speculated that discovering new natural products from well-characterized bacterial reference strains. The rationale behind this hypothesis stems from the observation that microbial genomes are rich in transcriptionally silent biosynthetic gene clusters (BGCs), Cite This: https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.joc.0c02492 strategy may also prove useful © XXXX American Chemical Society Angela A. potentially encoding for new and valuable chemical diversity. While an array of genome mining strategies have proved useful at accessing a portion of this hidden resource,9−13 we reasoned that MATRIX-enabled microbial biodiscovery might also prove eﬀective. To this end, we selected Streptomyces lincolnensis ACM-4234, a strain derived from S. lincolnensis NRRL2936 (ﬁrst described in 1969 by Shirling and Gottlieb)14 and a known producer of the clinically important antibiotic lincomycin A.15 Importantly, although the secondary metab- olism, genome, and biosynthetic capability of S. lincolnensis had been studied extensively,15−18 a MATRIX assessment of ACM- 4234 identiﬁed culture conditions capable of yielding a new suite of isomeric bianthracenes, lincolnenins A−D (1−4), with promising antibiotic and antitubercular properties. What follows is an account of the production, isolation, character- ization, and structure elucidation and an evaluation of the antibiotic properties of 1−4. A MATRIX cultivation analysis of S. lincolnensis ACM-4234 generated ×34 analytical extracts which, following HPLC- DAD-ESIMS proﬁling, revealed the production of a prominent metabolite, lincolnenin A (1) (C34H30O10), under only two conditions (ISP2 and oatmeal agar) (Figure S1). As a search of the primary scientiﬁc literature revealed no known bacterial natural products with this molecular formula, we elected to scale up and investigate the secondary metabolome of ACM- 4234. The solvent extract from a 21 day solid-phase oatmeal cultivation (×75 plates) was subjected to sequential solvent partitioning and gel and reversed-phase chromatography to yield a family of four new isomeric bianthracenes, lincolnenins A−D (1−4) (Figure S4). HRESI(+)MS analysis of 1 generated a molecular formula (C34H30O10) requiring 20 double bond equivalents (DBE). Analysis of the 1H NMR (CDCl3) data for 1 (Tables 1, 2, and S3 and Figures S5 and S6) revealed resonances attributed to two 3° methyls (δ H 1.20 and 1.60), a diastereotopic methylene (δ H 3.71), a 1,2,3-trisubstituted benzene (δ H 6.97, d, J 7.8 Hz; δ H 7.40 dd, J 8.3 and 7.8 Hz, rings C1/C2), and two H 10.13; δ chelated phenol moieties (δ further conﬁrmed by the 13C NMR data. A 1R*,2S*,1′R*,2′S* relative conﬁguration was assigned to 1 based on a diagnostic ROESY correlation between H-1/H-1′ and H3-13/H3-13′, together with biosynthetic considerations which mandated that both subunits (i.e., rings A1−C1 and rings A2−C2) share a common precursor and absolute conﬁguration. Given hindered rotation about the C-9/C-9′ bridge and the absence of NMR evidence for diastereomers, 1 was deemed to exist as a single C-9/C-9′ atropisomer. A visualization of the two diastereomers 1 and 1a demonstrated that only the 1R*,2S*,1’R*,2’S*,M* relative conﬁguration allowed for the ROESY correlations between H-1/H-1′ and H-8′/H-8 (Figure 2). Comparison of the experimental ECD spectrum for 1 with that calculated for the two enantiomers i and ii (Figure 3) conﬁrmed the 1R,2S,1′R,2′S,M absolute conﬁguration for lincolnenin A (1). It is worth noting that the calculated ECD spectra alone could not distinguish between diastereomers i (1R,2S,1′R,2′S,M) and iv (1S,2R,1′S,2′R,M) (Figure 3) or between ii and iii, highlighting the importance of pre-establishing the relative conﬁguration using the ROESY data.

Signiﬁcantly, the 1D and 2D NMR data for both 3 and 4 (Figure 1) conﬁrmed each incorporating two identical as subunit modulesin common with C-1′ to C-13′ (rings A2−C2) in 2. Similarly, 3 and 4 were assigned a 1R*,2S*,1′R*,2′S* relative conﬁguration based on a diagnostic ROESY correlation between H-1/H-1′ and H3-13/H3-13′, together with biosynthetic considerations. As in silico calculations revealed a modest C-8 to C-8′ barrier to rotation, 3 and 4 were deemed to be thermally interconvertable atropisomers. Supportive of this proposition, HPLC-DAD- ESMS analysis on a sample of 3 heated to 50 °C in MeOH revealed a 70:30 equilibration mixture of 3/4 after 5 h that remained constant for 29 h. With 1−4 in hand, we turned our attention to the closely related metabolite setomimycin (5) (Figure 8), ﬁrst reported in 1978 as an antimycobacterial and antitumor agent from the Japanese soil-derived Streptomyces pseudovenezuelae AM- 2947.19 A partial 1′R*,2′S* relative conﬁguration was reported for 5 in 1980,20 whereas the atropisomeric character was not acknowledged until 2014, when a 1S,1′S,2′R,P absolute conﬁguration was assigned on the basis of VCD and ECD measurements.21 By contrast, in our hands, lincolnenin A (1) underwent acid-mediated dehydration to a product identical in all respects to both literature data20,21 and an authentic commercial sample of 5 (NMR, [α]D, ECD), consistent with an enantiomeric 1S,1′R,2′S,M absolute conﬁguration (Figures S23−S25). As the earlier VCD/ECD-based conﬁgurational assignment was unconvincing, we independently compared the experimental ECD spectrum for 5, with calculated ECD spectra for the four stereoisomers (xiii) 1S,1′R,2′S,M, (xiv) 1R,1′S,2′R,P, (xv) 1S,1′R,2′S,P, and (xvi) 1R,1′S,2′R,M (Figure 8). Analysis of these data revealed a poor correlation between experimental and calculated ECD spectra, precluding an unambiguous absolute conﬁguration assignment. Based on all of these observations, we propose a reassignment of the absolute conﬁguration of setomimycin (5) to make it consistent with that assigned to lincolnenin A (1). The lincolnenins A−D (1−4) did not exhibit growth inhibitory activity against the Gram-negative bacteria Escher- ichia coli or the fungus Candida albicans, nor did they demonstrate cytotoxicity against human colorectal carcinoma (SW620) or human embryonic kidney (HEK293) cells (Figure S32). On the other hand, selected lincolnenins exhibited very signiﬁcant bactericidal activity against multiple Gram-positive pathogens, isolates lincolnenin A (1) was (Table 3). Of particular note, bactericidal against 6/8 Gram-positive pathogens tested (MIC99 < 2 μM) (Figure S33) and was particularly eﬀective against Mycobacterium tuberculosis H37Ra (MIC99 0.9 μM) (Figure S35), whereas the isomeric lincolnenins B−D (2−4) were either less potent or inactive, providing a promising structure activity relationship. As 1 was comparable in potency to the known antibiotic 5, and we had demonstrated that 1 could undergo dehydration to 5, this raised the possibility that 1 was a pro-drug of 5, undergoing in situ transformation during including several drug-resistant clinical https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.joc.0c02492 J. this study illustrates the value of our MATRIX approach to proﬁling culture conditions, even when applied to a well-documented and well-studied Streptomyces reference strain, Streptomyces lincolnensis ACM- 4234. Using this approach, we succeeded in activating the transcription, producing, isolating, characterizing, and identify- ing a series of new isomeric bianthracenes, lincolnenins A−D (1−4). Our success at solving the absolute conﬁgurations of 1−4, inclusive of chiral centers and atropisomeric linkages, led us the known Streptomyces antibiotic, setomimycin (5). Finally, we demon- strated that lincolnenin A (1) exhibits signiﬁcant bactericidal activity against a panel of Gram-positive pathogens, including drug-resistant clinical isolates, and M. tuberculosis H37Ra. That 1 is bactericidal against methicillin-, daptomycin-, and vancomycin-resistant Gram-positive pathogens suggests it acts through a mechanism of action uncompromised by signiﬁcant resistance pathways. Knowledge of the bactericidal properties of 1 could inform the future development of atropisomeric bianthracene antibiotics, including those capable of treating tuberculosis.

Circular dichroism spectra were recorded in MeOH using a JASCO J-810 spectropolarimeter using the following parameters; 0.1 cm path length cell at room temperature, concentration 0.02% (w/v), measurement range 500−200 nm, and bandwidth 1 nm. NMR spectra were obtained on a Bruker Advance DRX600 spectrometer in the solvents indicated and referenced to H7.24 and δ residual signals in deuterated solvents (δ C 77.23 ppm for CDCl3; δ C 49.15 ppm for methanol-d4). Strepto- myces lincolnensis ACM-4234 obtained from the Australian Collection of Microorganisms is derived from S. lincolnensis NRRL2936, a Gram- positive actinomycete ﬁrst isolated as part of the National Center for Agricultural Utilization Research in Illinois, USA, and described in 1969 by Shirling and Gottlieb.13

Microbioreactor Analytical Cultivation and Chemical Anal- ysis. A seed culture of S. lincolnensis ACM-4234 was transferred from an ISP2 agar culture to a sterile 24-well microbioreactor well containing either broth (1.5 mL) or solid (2.5 g) media for cultivation under three phases (i.e., liquid static, liquid shaken, and solid agar), known in-lab as the MATRIX.8,23 Brieﬂy, a combination of 11 culture media for broth (Table S1) was used for liquid static and liquid shaken, and 12 culture media (Table S2) were used for solid agar cultivation. A shaken broth culture plate was incubated on an orbital platform at 190 rpm, whereas all plates were incubated at 30 °C for 7 days. After the incubation, ACM-4234 cultures were extracted in situ with EtOAc (2 mL), and the decanted, ﬁltered organic layer was dried under N2 at 40 °C and redissolved in MeOH (40 μL). Aliquots (1 μL) of MeOH solutions were analyzed by UPLC-DAD, with data analyzed using Agilent ChemStation Open Lab CDS Rev. C.0103 (37) software and presented as a heat map (at 254 nm) using Prism 7.0 (GraphPad Software Inc., La Jolla, CA) (Figure S1). HPLC-DAD-MS Analysis of Oatmeal Agar Culture of ACM- 4234. The extract of a MATRIX solid-phase oatmeal cultivation of S. lincolnensis ACM-4234 obtained from three diﬀerent time points (7, 14, and 21 days, respectively) were subjected to HPLC-DAD-MS (Agilent 1100 series LC/MSD instrument using a Zorbax Eclipse XDB-C8 column, 4.6 × 150 mm, 5 μm, with a 1.0 mL/min ﬂow rate over 15 min gradient elution from 90% H2O/MeCN to MeCN with isocratic 0.05% formic acid modiﬁer) (Figures S2 and S3).

Scale-up Cultivation and Fractionation of Streptomyces lincolnensis ACM-4234. A sample of S. lincolnensis ACM-4234 was transferred from an ISP2 agar culture to oatmeal agar plates (×75 at 20 g each) and incubated at 30 °C for 21 days. After incubation, the agar was diced (∼1.5 cm × 1.5 cm), transferred to 2 L ﬂasks, and extracted with EtOAc (4 × 400 mL), with the decanted, ﬁltered organic layer concentrated to dryness in vacuo at 40 °C to yield a crude extract (3.94 g). The crude extract was sequentially triturated with n-hexane (3 × 50 mL) and MeOH (50 mL), which were concentrated in vacuo to aﬀord n-hexane (2.54 g) and MeOH (1.38 g) soluble fractions. The MeOH soluble fraction was further puriﬁed by gel chromatography (Sephadex LH-20, 2.5 × 86 cm column, 0.6 mL/ min isocratic elution with MeOH) to yield a fraction enriched in lincolnenins, which was subjected to semipreparative reversed-phase HPLC (Zorbax Eclipse XDB-C8, 5 μm, 9.4 × 250 mm, 3 mL/min ﬂow rate over 35 min isocratic elution at 55% H2O/MeCN with isocratic 0.01% TFA modiﬁer) to yield lincolnenins A (1) (tR = 26.3 min, 14.6 mg), B (2) (tR = 29.8 min, 9.4 mg), C (2) (tR = 28.4 min, 5.4 mg), and D (4) (tR = 24.2 min, 1.9 mg) (Scheme S1 and Figure S4).

Dehydration of Lincolnenin A (1) to Setomimycin (5). Lincolnenin A (1) (1 equiv.) was treated with p-TsOH (1 equiv.) in anhydrous toluene (5 mL) and heated at 40 °C for 2 h in an oil bath. The reaction mixture was concentrated in vacuo, and the residue was extracted with EtOAc (10 mL). The EtOAc was concentrated in vacuo, and the residue was puriﬁed by HPLC (Zorbax C8 column, 9.4 × 250 mm, 5 μm, with a 3.0 mL/min ﬂow rate over 20 min gradient elution from 90% H2O/MeCN to MeCN with isocratic 0.01% TFA modiﬁer) to aﬀord pure setomimycin (5) (0.5 mg), which is identical with the commercial standard (5*) purchased from BioAustralis (Smithﬁeld, NSW, Australia). ECD Calculations. Monte Carlo conformational searches were carried out by means of the Spartan’s 14 software using Merck Molecular Force Field. Two or three lowest conformers were chosen for ECD calculations, and then the conformers were initially optimized at the B3LYP/6-31g level in gas. The theoretical calculation of ECD was conducted in MeOH using time-dependent density functional theory at the B3LYP/6-311+g(d,p) level for all conformers lincolnenins A (i−iv), B (v−viii), C and D (ix−xii), and of setomimycin (xiii−xvi). Rotatory strengths for a total of 60 excited states were calculated. UV corrections (5 nm) were performed for lincolnenins A−D and at 10 nm for setomimycin. ECD spectra were generated using the program SpecDis 1.6 (University of Würzburg, Würzburg, Germany) and GraphPad Prism 5 (University of California San Diego, USA) from dipole-length rotational strengths by applying Gaussian band shapes with σ = 0.28 eV. See Figures S21−S24 and Tables S8−S15 for ECD calculation results.

Antibacterial Assays. The bacterium to be tested (Table 3) was streaked onto a tryptic soy agar plate and was incubated at 37 °C for 24 h. One colony was then transferred to fresh LB broth (15 mL), and the cell density was adjusted to 104−105 CFU/mL. The compounds to be tested were dissolved in DMSO and diluted with H2O to give 600 μM stock solution (20% DMSO), which was serially diluted with 20% DMSO to give concentrations from 600 to 0.2 μM in 20% DMSO. An aliquot (10 μL) of each dilution was transferred to a 96- Lincolnenin C (3): a yellow powder; [α]D Lincolnenin D (4): a yellow powder; [α]D Setomimycin (5): a yellow solid, [α]D well microtiter plate, and freshly prepared microbial broth (190 μL) was added to each well to give ﬁnal concentrations of 30−0.01 μM in 1% DMSO. The plates were incubated at 37 °C for 24 h, and the optical density of each well was measured spectrophotometrically at 600 nm using POLARstar Omega plate (BMG LABTECH, Oﬀenburg, Germany). Antimycobacterial Assay. Mycobacterium tuberculosis H37Ra (ATCC 25177) was grown until early mid-log phase in 7H9 liquid medium (Difco) containing 0.2% glycerol, 0.05% Tween80, 0.5% bovine serum albumin, 0.2% dextrose, and 0.085% sodium chloride. Single cell suspensions of independent cultures were prepared by centrifuging the bacterial cultures for 10 min at 130g at room temperature and then diluted to an optical density (o.d.; 600 nm) of 0.02. Test compounds were dissolved in DMSO and diluted with H2O to give a 600 μM stock solution (20% DMSO), which was serially diluted with 20% DMSO to give concentrations from 600 to 0.2 μM in 20% DMSO. An aliquot (10 μL) of each dilution was transferred to a 96-well microtiter plate, and freshly prepared mycobacterial broth (OD 0.02, 190 μL) was added to each well to give ﬁnal concentrations of 30−0.01 μM in 1% DMSO. The plates were incubated for 7 days at 37 °C and 5% CO2. Bacterial growth in the presence of lincolnenins A−D (1− 4) and setomimycin (5*) and setomimycin (5) (200 μL aliquots) was monitored in 96-well plates by OD600 measurements. To analyze bacterial survival, serial dilutions of culture material were plated on Middlebrook 7H10 plates supplemented with 10% oleic acid/albumin/dextrose catalase (OADC; Middlebrook) and 0.5% glycerol. Plates were incubated at 37 °C for 3 weeks and colonies enumerated to calculate colony- forming units (CFU). Isoniazid (INH) was used as a positive control (20 μg/mL in H2O) (Figure S35).
